30","1417":"1417","1317":"1317","Lewynsmede, Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","St Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lewynesmede, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1346–1390":"1346–1390","1348–Male":"1348–Deceased","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1364–1390":"1364–1390","1378–1426":"1378–1426","1378–1430":"1378–1430","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1314–1386":"1314–1386","1317–Female":"1317–Deceased","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","1430":"1430","1417":"1417","1317":"1317","Lewynsmede, Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","St Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Lewynesmede, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stephens","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Stevens  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stevens","meanings":["English (London), Flemish, Dutch, and North German: patronymic from the personal name   Steven  . The surname of Flemish origin is also found in the Walloon part of Belgium. In North America, the English form of the surname has also absorbed some like-sounding Jewish names and various other European cognates, e.g. Greek   Stefanidis  , Serbian <b>Stevanović</b> (see   Stevanovic  ), Slovenian and Slovak <b>Štefanič</b> (see   Stefanic  )."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":36,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Fitz Stephens Baron of Llewynsmede was born in 1346, in Gloucestershire, England, his father, John Fitz Stephens III, was 33 and his mother, Joanna Spelly, was 29. He married Audrey De Castell in 1378, in Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1390, in Bristol, Gloucestershire, England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1346–1390":"1346–1390","1348–Male":"1348–Surnud","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1364–1390":"1364–1390","1378–1426":"1378–1426","1378–1430":"1378–1430","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1314–1386":"1314–1386","1317–Female":"1317–Surnud","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","1430":"1430","1417":"1417","1317":"1317","Lewynsmede, Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","St Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lewynesmede, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1346–1390":"1346–1390","1348–Male":"1348–Kuollut","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1364–1390":"1364–1390","1378–1426":"1378–1426","1378–1430":"1378–1430","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1314–1386":"1314–1386","1317–Female":"1317–Kuollut"